Yes — you’re pointing at something real about how thinking works. Metaphors and rhetorical devices are powerful partly because they map structure from one domain onto another. When the mapping preserves key relationships, the insight transfers.

This idea shows up in several fields:

1. Cognitive science: metaphor as structure-mapping

Researchers like George Lakoff and Mark Johnson argue that much of human reasoning uses conceptual metaphors.
Example mappings:
	•	Argument → War (“defend a position”, “attack a claim”)
	•	Time → Motion (“the deadline is approaching”)
	•	Understanding → Seeing (“I see your point”)

These aren’t just figures of speech; they’re ways the brain organizes relationships.

So metaphor works because it transfers relational structure, not just words.

⸻

2. Mathematics: analogy and isomorphism

In math and physics, the same thing happens more formally.

A relationship in one system can appear in another system with the same structure but different meaning.

Examples:

Domain A	Domain B	Shared structure
Electric circuits	Fluid flow	current ↔ flow rate
Wave optics	Quantum mechanics	wave equations
Heat diffusion	Probability	diffusion equations

When the structures match, mathematicians say the systems are isomorphic or analogous.

So what metaphor does in language, isomorphism does in math.

⸻

3. Orthogonal domains and translation

Your phrase “orthogonal domains” is a nice way to put it.

Different domains can share the same relational skeleton even if the objects are totally different.

Example skeleton:

something spreads over time
rate depends on gradient
system smooths differences

That same pattern appears in:
	•	heat diffusion
	•	rumor spreading
	•	chemical concentration
	•	probability distributions
	•	price equilibration in markets

Different substrates — same underlying relational pattern.

⸻

4. Why rhetorical devices help reasoning

Good metaphors act like compression algorithms.

Instead of explaining a long structure, you say:

“It’s like gravity pulling ideas together.”

And the listener imports the entire relationship system of gravity:
	•	attraction
	•	distance
	•	mass / weight
	•	orbits
	•	equilibrium

All of that structure transfers instantly.

⸻

5. The danger (and power)

The catch is that metaphors aren’t perfect translations.

Some structure transfers correctly, some doesn’t.

For example:

“Markets are like ecosystems.”

Useful parallels:
	•	competition
	•	niches
	•	adaptation

But the analogy breaks if pushed too far because the rules differ.

So the skill is identifying which relationships actually carry over.

⸻

6. A deeper way to say what you said

Your idea can be expressed like this:

Insight happens when a relational pattern discovered in one domain is translated into another domain where it wasn’t previously recognized.

Mathematics formalizes that translation.

Metaphor performs it informally.

Both are doing the same core operation:

mapping structure across domains.

⸻

7. Why this matters for creativity

Many breakthroughs come from exactly this move:
	•	calculus ← geometry + motion
	•	thermodynamics ← statistical mechanics
	•	neural networks ← biology metaphors
	•	information theory ← communication metaphor

Discovery often happens when someone realizes:

“This pattern over here is the same pattern over there.”

